T1  - Sparse Signals in the Cross-Section of Returns
AU  - CHINCO, ALEX
AU  - CLARK-JOSEPH, ADAM D.
AU  - YE, MAO
Y1  - 2019/02/01
PY  - 2019
DA  - 2019/02/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.12733
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 449
EP  - 492
VL  - 74
IS  - 1
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.12733
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT This paper applies the Least Absolute Shrinkage and Selection Operator (LASSO) to make rolling one-minute-ahead return forecasts using the entire cross-section of lagged returns as candidate predictors. The LASSO increases both out-of-sample fit and forecast-implied Sharpe ratios. This out-of-sample success comes from identifying predictors that are unexpected, short-lived, and sparse. Although the LASSO uses a statistical rule rather than economic intuition to identify predictors, the predictors it identifies are nevertheless associated with economically meaningful events: the LASSO tends to identify as predictors stocks with news about fundamentals.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - A Test of the Modigliani-Miller Invariance Theorem and Arbitrage in Experimental Asset Markets
AU  - CHARNESS, GARY
AU  - NEUGEBAUER, TIBOR
Y1  - 2019/02/01
PY  - 2019
DA  - 2019/02/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.12736
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 493
EP  - 529
VL  - 74
IS  - 1
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.12736
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT Modigliani and Miller show that the total market value of a firm is unaffected by a repackaging of asset return streams to equity and debt if pricing is arbitrage-free. We investigate this invariance theorem in experimental asset markets, finding value-invariance for assets of identical risks when returns are perfectly correlated. However, exploiting price discrepancies has risk when returns have the same expected value but are uncorrelated, in which case the law of one price is violated. Discrepancies shrink in consecutive markets, but persist even with experienced traders. In markets where overall trader acuity is high, assets trade closer to parity.
ER  - 

